column6: Doctolib began as a software service provider helping healthcare professionals manage consultation scheduling and patient engagement. However, over the last year or so, it’s made a concerted effort to expand into telehealth. Doctolib charges doctors 79 euros per month to use its video consultation platform. The company’s website states that 3,500 practitioners use its platform and have performed over 150,000 consultations since September 2018. Earlier this month, Doctolib said it was experiencing a 40% increase in in-bound requests from doctors looking to equip themselves for Covid-19-related televisits. To help bridge the gap, Doctolib subsequently announced it would allow all doctors in France to use its video consultation platform for free for the duration of the pandemic. It also plans to reimburse the 3,500 doctors already paying for the service.

column3: A healthcare technology company that handles everything from online diagnosis to the delivery of medication.
column6: DTC telehealth startup Ro has partnered with patient engagement startup Memora Health (discussed further below) to implement a free Covid-19 televisit service, which includes interacting with a chatbot. If the chatbot determines a patient is experiencing viral symptoms or has visited a high-risk area, it directs the patient to Ro’s telehealth service, which connects them to a licensed provider via video or phone. If the physician then determines the patient is “high risk” for Covid-19, Ro coordinates with the patient’s state health department to arrange treatment at a local facility.  Ro’s initial focus is on rolling this out to states like Washington, California, and New York, which have experienced the most severe outbreaks; however, it intends to make the service available nationwide in the coming days.

column3: A mobile app providing fast and easy access to some of the best doctors, psychologists, and other healthcare providers.
column6: Doctor On Demand connects patients with board-certified physicians for video-based telehealth visits through smartphones, tablets, and desktop computers. It provides services directly to consumers as well as indirectly through employers and health plans. The company has designed and implemented an online Covid-19 assessment for patients to use before seeking care. The assessment takes roughly 2 minutes to complete and asks a total of 8 questions, including, “Do you have a cough or shortness of breath?” It provides a risk-level assessment along with educational material. Those who screen as especially high-risk are encouraged to connect with a doctor via a virtual video visit.

column3: A mobile app that uses AI to deliver personalized primary care better, faster, and cheaper.
column6: K Health is a digital health company that offers free personalized healthcare. The company has created an AI-driven, text-based primary care solution that allows users to see how doctors diagnose and treat people with similar symptoms. If users then wish to see a physician, they can pay $19 to continue their chat with a licensed primary care provider, or they can elect to pay $39/year for unlimited chats. The company recently waived the $19 fee for coronavirus-based virtual care visits. According to its website, K Health will offer those seeking Covid-19 advice free, unlimited access to US doctors for 14 days.

column3: Combines deep technology with the expertise of board-certified physicians to provide text-based primary care anytime, anywhere.
column6: 98point6‘s mobile application allows on-demand, 24/7 access to primary care physicians through a chat-based interface. After a brief interaction with the app’s Automated Assistant, users are connected to a licensed primary care provider who has already been briefed by the AI assistant. Using secure in-app messaging, the physician can answer questions, assess symptoms (including with photo and video), and diagnose health issues. In late January, 98point6 added Covid-19 screening questions to its app. When patients report flu-like symptoms, they’re immediately connected to a physician. If they also report that they’ve traveled to at-risk areas or have been in close contact with someone testing positive, they’re flagged as high-risk and prioritized accordingly.  98point6’s chief medical officer reports that the company has seen “large growth in enrollment and utilization” in the last month and a half.
